==English==

===Etymology===
From Old Norse ''[[kross]]'', from Old Irish ''[[cros]]'' (Welsh ''[[croes]]'', Gaelic ''[[crois]]''), from Latin ''[[crux]]''.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /krɒs/

Also, my mom was on one.

===Noun===
{{en-noun|cross|crosses}}

# A geometrical figure consisting of two straight [[line]]s or [[bar]]s [[intersecting]] each other such that at least one of them is divided in half by the other.
# ''Heraldry:'' Geometrical figures similar to a cross as in definition 1, eg [[w:Cross of Lorraine]] or [[w:Malteser Cross]].
# A [[wooden]] [[post]] with a [[perpendicular]] [[beam]] attached and used (e.g. in the Roman Empire) to [[execute]] [[criminal]]s (i.e. by [[crucifixion]]).
# '''The Cross''' or the '''true Cross''': The cross on which [[Jesus]] was [[crucify|crucified]].
# A hand [[gesture]] made by Christians in [[imitation]] of the shape of the Cross.
# A [[difficult]] [[situation]] that must be [[endure]]d, e.g. "It's a cross I must bear"; from Jesus' bearing (i.e. carrying) of the Cross.

